ce:section.ce:para:
The sensing performance of the CC/CeO2/CNPs mesh on melamine was tested under different illumination conditions (Fig. 5
                        a-c). It is observed that the DPV current decreases in proportion with the increase of melamine concentration, and illumination effectively enhances the current response. In the dark, the linear equation is I (μA) = -1.03C (nM) + 202 (R2 = 0.964) (0–100 nM). The sensitivity and the lowest detection limit (LOD) (3σ method) are determined as 1.03 μA•nM−1 cm−2 and 1.37 nM. Under a 200 W Xe lamp, the linear equation is I (μA) = -1.46C (nM) + 259 (R2 = 0.992) (0–100 nM). The sensitivity and the LOD are determined as 1.46 μA•nM−1 cm−2 and 0.970 nM. Under a 400 W Xe lamp, there are two linear ranges, the linear equations are I (μA) = -5.15C + 273 (R2 = 0.984) (0–30 nM) and I (μA) = -1.75C + 172 (R2 = 0.988) (30–60 nM) respectively. Their sensitivities are 5.15 μA•nM−1cm−2 and 1.75 μA•nM−1 cm−2, respectively, LOD is 0.275 nM. The sensitivity under a 400 W Xe lamp irradiation is 4.98 times higher than that in the dark. The LOD is 0.275 nM, which is much lower than the international safety detection threshold (20 μM) (Liao, Chen, Chang, & Zen, 2011). From the above results, it is found that 400 W Xe lamp irradiation makes sensitivity increase as 4.98 times and LOD decrease by 73.3%. The sensing performance to melamine under illumination is significantly improved compared with previous work in terms of sensitivity and LOD (Table 1
                        ).
